Phase 1: The Finops Data and Storage foundation

Step 1: The network Perimeter (The Rapid Build)
-----------------------------------------------

Since you mastered the 3-tier VPC in your last project, we need to quickly rebuild that fortress to house our new databases.

1.Go to the VPC Dashboard > Create VPC.
2.Select VPC and more (We will use the wizard this time for speed, so we can focus on the advanced FinOps features).
3.Name tag auto-generation: cloudbite-global
4.IPv4 CIDR block: 10.0.0.0/16
5.Number of Availability Zones: 2
6.Number of public subnets: 2
7.Number of Private Subnets: 4
8.NAT gateways: In 1 AZ (FinOps tip: 1 NAT is cheaper than 2. For a startup budget, we accept the slight risk of an AZ-specific NAT failure to save $32/month).
9.VPC endpoints: S3 Gateway (Free, and saves NAT data processing costs).
10. Click Create VPC. Wait for the green success checks.

Step 2: Automated Storage (S3 Intelligent-Tierring_)

Next, we create the bucket for your e-commerce product images. We will configure it so that old inventory automatically moves to cheaper storage, eliminating idle storage waste.

1.Go to the S3 Dashboard and click Create bucket.
2.Bucket name: cloudbite-assets-[your-name]-[random-numbers] (Must be globally unique).
3.Region: us-east-1 (N. Virginia).
4.Leave all defaults (Block all public access should remain ON) and click Create bucket.
5.Click into your new bucket and go to the Properties tab.
6.Scroll down to Intelligent-Tiering Archive Configurations and click Create configuration.
7.Name: Zombie-Asset-Prevention
8.Status: Enable
9.Archive rule actions: 
* Check Archive Access tier (Data moves here after 90 days of no access).
* Check Deep Archive Access tier (Data moves here after 180 days).

Click Create

Step 3: The primary Database (RDS Multi-AZ)

Now we deploy the relational database in your private data subnets.

A.Subnet Group

1.Go to RDS > Subnet groups > Create DB subnet group.
2.Name: cloudbite-db-subnets
3.VPC: Select your new cloudbite-global-vpc.
4.Add subnets: Select your two AZs (us-east-1a and us-east-1b), then select the CIDR blocks for your two deepest private subnets (e.g., 10.0.144.0/20 and 10.0.160.0/20). Click Create.


B. Launch the Database

1.Go to Databases > Create database.
2.Creation method: Standard create.
3.Engine options: MySQL.
4.Templates: Dev/Test (This enables Multi-AZ without the massive Enterprise minimum instance sizes).
5.Settings: Name it cloudbite-primary. Set your Master username (admin) and a password.
6.Instance configuration: Burstable classes > db.t3.micro.
7.Availability and durability: Select Create a standby instance (Multi-AZ).
8.Connectivity:
  * VPC: cloudbite-global-vpc.
  * DB Subnet group: cloudbite-db-subnets.
  * Public access: No.
Security_group: Select choose the existing -> Cloudbite--db-sg  and Remove the default one
9.Scroll down and click Create database.



Now we are going to build the critical part of your project Disaster Recovery  plan : The Pilot Light

If a massive hurricane takes down the entire N. Virginia data center, your compute instances (EC2) will die, but compute is stateless and easily replaceable. Data, however, is the lifeblood of an e-commerce company. We need to ensure that every time a user creates an account or updates their shopping cart in N. Virginia, that data is secretly copied to the opposite side of the country in milliseconds.

Here is how we set up the cross-region Read Replica


Step 4: The Cross Region "Pilot Light " Replica

1.Stay in the N. Virginia (us-east-1) region in your RDS Dashboard.
2.Click on Databases and select your cloudbite-primary instance (ensure its status is "Available").
3.In the top right corner, click the Actions dropdown menu and select Create read replica.
3.Destination Region: Scroll down and select US West (Oregon). (AWS will automatically handle the encrypted cross-region network backbone for you).
4.DB instance identifier: Name it cloudbite-dr-replica.
5.Instance configuration: Select Burstable classes > db.t3.micro.
6.MultiAZ deployment : Select Single DB instance
   *Senior FinOps Tip: Why single? Because in a "Pilot Light" scenario, we don't want to pay double for a standby database in a region that isn't even receiving traffic. If we actually have to failover to Oregon during a disaster, we can modify this replica to Multi-AZ later.

7.Connectivity: For the Virtual Private Cloud (VPC), you can select the Default VPC for the Oregon region for this lab. (Note: In a true enterprise environment, you would use an IaC tool like Terraform to build an identical clone of your cloudbite-global-vpc in Oregon before this step).
9.Public access: Ensure this is set to No.
10.Scroll to the very bottom and click Create read replica.

Here is how you would survive a Black Friday disaster: 

If us-east-1 goes completely offline, you would log into the Oregon console, select this replica, click Actions, and choose Promote. Within minutes, this read-only database breaks its ties with the dead primary and becomes a fully functional, standalone read/write database. Your business stays alive.

