Phase2: High Performance Compute ( the spot strategy)


Step 5: The Security Layer 
Before we launch servers, we need to allow traffic to reach them.

1.Go to the EC2 Dashboard > Security Groups > Create security group.
2.Create the ALB Security Group:
  Name: cloudbite-alb-sg
  VPC: cloudbite-global-vpc
  Inbound Rules: Allow HTTP (80) from 0.0.0.0/0.

3.Create the App Servers Security Group:
  Name: cloudbite-app-sg
  VPC: cloudbite-global-vpc
  Inbound Rules: Allow HTTP (80) where the source is cloudbite-alb-sg. (This enforces that no one can bypass the load balancer
  Click Create.

Step 6: The Lauch Template 

This is the blueprint for your servers.

1.Go to Launch Templates (under Instances on the left) > Create launch template.
2.Name: cloudbite-blackfriday-lt
3.AMI: Select Amazon Linux 2023.
4.Instance type: Select t3.small (We will override this dynamically in the ASG step).
5.Key pair: Select Proceed without a key pair. (We rely on SSM for secure access, as established in your previous architecture).
6.Network settings: Do not select a subnet. For Security groups, choose cloudbite-app-sg.
7.Expand Advanced details:

IAM instance profile: Select your SSM role (e.g., AppServerSSMRole if you still have it from the previous project, or create a quick one with AmazonSSMManagedInstanceCore).

User data: Paste this script to start a web server and display the instance type, so you can actually see the Spot instances working later:

#!/bin/bash
yum update -y
yum install -y httpd jq
systemctl start httpd
systemctl enable httpd
TOKEN=$(curl -X PUT "http://169.254.169.254/latest/api/token" -H "X-aws-ec2-metadata-token-ttl-seconds: 21600")
INSTANCE_TYPE=$(curl -H "X-aws-ec2-metadata-token: $TOKEN" -s http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/instance-type)
echo "<h1>CloudBite Black Friday API</h1><p>Running on highly optimized instance: <strong>$INSTANCE_TYPE</strong></p>" > /var/www/html/index.html

8.Click Create launch template.

Step 7:The Finops AutoScaling Group

This is the core of the cost-optimization strategy.


1.Go to Auto Scaling Groups > Create Auto Scaling group.
2.Name: cloudbite-finops-asg. Select cloudbite-blackfriday-lt and click Next.
3.Network: Select cloudbite-global-vpc and choose your two Private App Subnets.
4.Instance type requirements (The FinOps Magic):
   Do NOT select "Adhere to launch template".
   Select Combine purchase options and instance types
   Under Allocation Strategies, set:
     On-Demand base capacity: 1 (This guarantees at least 1 server is always immune to Spot terminations).
     On-Demand percentage above base: 20% (This means for every 10 servers you scale up, 2 are On-Demand, 8 are heavily discounted Spot).
     Under Instance types, AWS will auto-suggest compatible types (like t3.small, t3a.small, t2.small). Keep these! If AWS runs out of t3.small spot capacity, it will automatically launch a t2.small instead.

5.Click Next
6.Load balancing: Select Attach to a new load balancer.
  Choose Application Load Balancer -> Internet-facing.
  Subnets: Select your two Public Subnets.
  Target group: Create new (cloudbite-tg).

7.Click Next until you reach Group size and scaling.
  Desired: 2, Min: 2, Max: 10.
  Check Target tracking scaling policy -> CPU utilization at 50%. (During Black Friday, you want to scale up before the server maxes out).

8.Skip the rest and click Create Auto Scaling group.

Verification CheckPoint: 

Go to the EC2 Dashboard and click on Instances. You should see a couple of servers spinning up. Look at the Lifecycle column—you should see at least one marked "Spot" and one marked "normal" (On-Demand).

If you grab your ALB's DNS name and paste it into your browser, you should see your web page proudly displaying the instance type it landed on.







